Key Match Events: Bukayo Saka scored an equalizing goal in the final minute of regular time.
England forced extra time when Saka scored with their first shot on target.
Xherdan Shaqiri hit the angle of post and bar with a corner in extra time.
Jordan Pickford made an excellent save from Zeki Amdouni in extra time.
Switzerland’s Manuel Akanji missed the decisive penalty in the shootout, saving England’s victory.
Trent Alexander-Arnold scored the winning penalty for England.
Pre-Game Insights: Murat Yakin’s team dominated for much of the second half, raising the prospect of Gareth Southgate’s 100th game in charge being his last.
Gareth Southgate introduced Cole Palmer, Eberechi Eze, and Luke Shaw with 12 minutes left.
Harry Kane was off the pace, and Southgate’s decisions were criticized for not working.
Post-Match Reflections: Gareth Southgate kept defying the narrative around English football by managing his team effectively.
Southgate’s faith in players like Bukayo Saka and Trent Alexander-Arnold paid off in the shootout.
England will need to be better against the Netherlands in the next round.
Miscellaneous Highlights: Kieran Trippier played on the left flank despite concerns about Dan Ndoye.
Declan Rice seemed more imposing, and Bellingham was more involved in the match.
